# Geographic information system (gis)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Geographic Information System (GIS) is a spatial system that creates, manages, analyzes, and maps all types of data.

## Purpose
We use GIS for R&D to collect, analyze, visualize, and store geospatial data, integrating the spatial dimension into our analyses.

## How it works
To use GIS, we need to mobilize data collection tools to collect data and utilize a GIS software (open source or commercial) to analyze this data and generate information. This involves geolocating physical elements or modeling abstract elements.

## Requirements
Effective use of GIS requires technical skills in georeferenced data collection and analysis, as well as soft skills in problem-solving.

## Reflections
When using GIS tools for R&D purposes, it's essential to keep in mind the principles that apply to information management in general.

## Related methods (if any)
GIS is often used in conjunction with Data Visualization.

## License
GIS software is available under various licenses, including free or open-source options such as QGIS and commercial options like ESRI ArcGIS.

## Examples
Examples of GIS use in R&D can be found at the United Nations Development Programme's website, where they have implemented GIS technologies for sustainable development.
